{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ἦθος</b>, εος, τό <br /> (compare ἔθος), <b>an accustomed place</b>: hence, in <i>plural</i>, <b>haunts</b> or <b>abodes</b> of animals, μετά τ᾽ ἤθεα καὶ νομὸν ἵππων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 6.511; [σύας] ἔρξαν κατὰ ἤθεα κοιμηθῆναι 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.411 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of lions, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.125 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of fish, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Oppianus Anazarbensis Epicus “Halieutica - Poetae Bucolici et Didactici” 1.93 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; of <b>the abodes of men</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 167, 525, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.15, 157, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Supplices” 64 (Lyric poetry), 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Helena” 274, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 865e, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Mundo” 398b33 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἔλεγον ἐξ ἠθέων τὸν ἥλιον ἀνατεῖλαι away from his <b>accustomed place</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.142 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of plants, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.AD: Callistratus Sophista “Statuarum descriptiones” 7 \">Refs 4th c.AD+</a>]: <i>metaphorically</i>, with play on <i>signification</i> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 277a. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>custom, usage</b>: in <i>plural</i>, <b>manners, customs</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 137, “Th.” 66, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.30, 35, 4.106, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 2.61; τρόποι καὶ ἤθη 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 896c \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐθρέψω Ξέρξην ἐν τοῖς αὐτοῖς ἤ[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\". [prev. work] 695e; φθείρουσιν ἤθη χρήσθ᾽ ὁμιλίαι κακαί “PHib.” 1.7.94 (5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Fragmenta” 1024 = 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus 218); τοῖς ἤθεσιν ἁπλοῦς 1st c.BC: Diodorus Siculus Historicus 5.21. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>disposition, character</b>, ἐπίκλοπον ἦθος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 67, 78; ἦ. ἐμφυές 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 11(10).21 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἀκίχητα ἤ., of Zeus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 187; τοὐμὸν ἦ. παιδεύειν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 595 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὦ μιαρὸν ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Ant.” 746 \">Refs</a>]; τὸ τῆς πόλεως ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Isocrates Orator 2.31 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; βελτίων τῆς πόλεως τὸ ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 20.14 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; especially <b>moral character</b>, opposed to διάνοια, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1139a1 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; as the result of habit, τὸ πᾶν ἦ. διὰ ἔθος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 792e, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Eudemia” 1220a39; ἦ. ἀνθρώπῳ δαίμων 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 119 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἦ. πηγὴ βίου Stoic. cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.AD: Stobaeus, Joannes 2.7.1\">Refs 5th c.AD+</a>]; τῆς ψυχῆς, τῆς γνώμης, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 400d, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 61.16: frequently opposed to πάθος, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1356a23 (_plural_), etc.; ἠθῶν τε καὶ παθῶν μίμησις 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “Epistula ad Pompeium” 3; τὸ ἦ. πρᾶος 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Phaedrus” 243c: less frequently in _dative_, ἀγοραῖος τῷ ἤ. 4th-3rd c.BC: Theophrastus Philosophus “Characteres” 6.2, compare “Inscription Magn.” 164.3 (1st-2nd c.AD)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>plural</i>, <b>traits, characteristics</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 402d, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Nicomachea” 1144b4 (in _sing._, τὸ τῆς ἀνδρείας ἦ. 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 836d)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: seldom in <i>plural</i>, of an individual, στερρὸν τὰ ἤθεα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “ἐπιστολαί” 11; ἱερὸς κατὰ τὰ ἤθη 2nd c.AD: Athenaeus Epigrammaticus 1.1e. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__II.2.b</b></Level4> of outward <b>bearing</b>, ὡς ἱλαρὸν τὸ ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Symposium” 8.3; ὑγρότης ἤθους 4th c.BC: Lycurgus Orator 33 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὑψηλὸς τῷ ἤ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Dio” 4 \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: in <i>plural</i>, of facial expression, ὀφθαλμῶν ἤθη [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “de gymnastica” 25. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__II.2.c</b></Level4> in Rhet., <b>delineation of character</b>, ἦ. ἔχουσιν οἱ λόγοι ἐν ὅσοις δήλη ἡ προαίρεσις [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1395b13; ἦ. ἐμφαίνειν 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.200S. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; especially opposed to πάθος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Longinus Rhetor 9.15, etc.\">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]; κατ᾽ ἦ. λέγεσθαι, opposed to κατὰ πάθος, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “de Compositione Verborum” 22, compare “Lys.” 19: in _plural_, πραγμάτων καὶ ἠθῶν 1st c.BC: Philodemus Philosophus “περὶ ποιημάτων” 5.5; ἐν πάθεσι καὶ ἤθεσιν 4th c.BC: Demetrius Phalereus Rhetor “Demetrius on Style” 28, etc.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; so of works of art, ἡ Ζεύξιδος γραφὴ οὐδὲν ἔχει ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Poetica” 1450a29; πάθος καὶ ἦ. καὶ σχημάτων χρῆσις 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “Varia Historia” 4.3; πολλὰ ἤθη ἐπιφαίνει 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Heroicus” 2.10 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; also of Music, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Sextus Empiricus Philosophus “adversus Mathematicos” 6.49. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>] <br /><Level4><b>__II.2.d</b></Level4> <b>dramatis persona</b>, εἰσάγει ἄνδρα ἢ γυναῖκα ἢ ἄλλο τι ἦ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Poetica” 1450a11, +others \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> also of animals, ἦ. τὸ πρὸς τοκέων (probable reading for ἔθος) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 727, compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 1219, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 375e, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 487a12 (_plural_); τὸ ἦ. ἀσθενής, of a bird, [prev. work] 615a18 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of things, <b>nature, kind</b>, παρὰ δ᾽ ἦ. ἑκάστῳ (to each of the four elements) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Empedocles Poeta Philosophus 17.28; τοῦ πυρετοῦ 2nd c.AD: Galenus Medicus 7.353. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.4</b></Level3> ἐν ἤθει <b>tactfully</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"compare (ἠθικός 11.2), προσφέρεσθαι τοῖς ἁμαρτάνουσιν 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.73e. compare 5th c.AD: Hermias Alexandrinus Philosophus “in Platonis Phaedrum scholia” p.195A. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; διὰ μέτριον ἦθος, of the expression δοκεῖ μοι, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th c.AD: Stephanus Medicus “in Hp.” 1.59D. \">Refs 7th c.AD+</a>]","strongNumber":"G2239","accentedUnicode":"ἦθος","relatedNos":